3. LATIN AND GREEK PROPER NAMus.——Of these there are not less than sourteen thousand found in our large dictionaries. These names are pronounced, not after the Continental method, much less after the doubt- fully resurrected meth0d3 but in all cases after the Walkerian or English system. This is a consideration of vast importance. A class taught the “hard'' or Roman mode of pronunciation will, in multitudes of instances, call these names wrong. This is daily obvi- ous to any instructor who uses the Latin method, more especially, if he thinks it worth while to conform to standard authority. The English pronunciation brings with it convenience, consiste ncy, and accuracy in proper names. The student does not need to pronounce Caesar, Ki—sar, when he reads the text and Se-zar when he translates.

It should be borne in mind, too, that several thousand classical words have been omitted in the most recent editions of our great dictionaries. The omission em- braces monosyllables, a large number of dissyllables, words of rare occurrence, and many fictitious names found in the poets. The number of classical names is vastly larger than a mere passing acquaintance might lead scholars to suppose.
